  {
    storyId: '5078414',
    title: "Scientists Cautious on Tamiflu's Impact on Bird Flu",
    date: 'Sun, 01 Jan 2006 05:00:00 +0000'.to_datetime,
    url_link: 'http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5078414',
    audio_link: 'http://pd.npr.org/anon.npr-mp3/npr/atc/2006/01/20060101_atc_04.mp3?dl=1',
    paragraphs: ["DEBBIE ELLIOTT, host:", "Governments around the world are building massive stockpiles of the antiviral drug Tamiflu. In the US, many consumers have purchased their own stocks of the drug. It's all a response to the possibility of a severe flu pandemic. What's unclear, though, is how effective Tamiflu would be if a pandemic actually strikes. NPR's Jon Hamilton reports.", "JON HAMILTON reporting:", "Let's say a pandemic does arrive. The US plan calls for handing out millions of doses of Tamiflu to reduce the death toll. Scientists say that's a reasonable approach since there's no vaccine for bird flu and Tamiflu appears to do some good. But the drug is no panacea. Here's Dr. Anthony Fauci, the director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases. He is testifying before the House Committee on International Relations.", "Dr. ANTHONY FAUCI (Director, National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases): I want to caution the committee that we cannot equate stockpiling and availability of Tamiflu with preparedness. We have no hard scientific data of how well this antiviral will perform under the conditions of a pandemic.", "HAMILTON: Fauci says Tamiflu doesn't cure even regular flu.", "Dr. FAUCI: In seasonal flu, what this antiviral does is diminish the duration of symptoms by approximately a day and a half.", "HAMILTON: That's because Tamiflu doesn't kill the virus; it just slows it down so the body's immune system can catch up. Other scientists are more positive about Tamiflu and other existing antiviral drugs. Dr. Frederick Hayden is with the University of Virginia School of Medicine.", "Dr. FREDERICK HAYDEN (University of Virginia School of Medicine): The public needs to recognize that there are limitations with our current agents, that these are not magic bullets, but at the same time that these drugs can provide a great deal of benefit.", "HAMILTON: Which could mean the difference between life and death for some people infected with bird flu. Hayden says one of the limitations of Tamiflu is that it needs to be taken within a day or two after a person gets sick.", "Dr. HAYDEN: Once someone is in a desperate situation with advanced pneumonia, there's no evidence that antiviral treatment really does any good at that stage.", "HAMILTON: That's a problem with bird flu because patients often don't get diagnosed immediately. Hayden says another limitation is that ordinary flu viruses have shown they can develop resistance to Tamiflu.", "Dr. HAYDEN: We've known for some years that Tamiflu-treated patients can shed resistant virus. It's been seen in about one in five children, for example, treated for conventional human influenza.", "HAMILTON: More recently, scientists have found signs that bird flu virus also can develop resistance to Tamiflu. A recent study said two patients in Vietnam died after the virus became resistant.", "Hayden says that in spite of Tamiflu's limitations, it makes sense for governments to purchase large quantities. One reason is that even a small decrease in the severity of a flu pandemic would be worth the billions of dollars countries are spending on Tamiflu.", "Dr. HAYDEN: Drug stockpiling will likely be cost saving in the long run 'cause you need to balance that with respect to the enormous economic impact that a major influenza event could have.", "HAMILTON: Fauci, the government scientist, agrees Tamiflu could make a difference if a pandemic struck soon. But in his testimony before Congress, he pointed out that it will be years before the US stockpile is complete.", "Dr. FAUCI: The strategy is ultimately to have 75 million treatment courses to cover 25 percent of the population. We have assurances from the company that we will get to 20 million treatment courses by December of '06 and be 75 million by the summer or spring of '07.", "HAMILTON: That may be optimistic. Roche, the company that makes Tamiflu, is scrambling to fill orders, and other countries placed their orders for the drug well before the US did. Jon Hamilton, NPR News. Transcript provided by NPR, Copyright NPR."]
